    <h2>What is a Money Market Fund?</h2>
    <p>A money market fund is a type of mutual fund or Exchange-Traded Fund (ETF) that invests in highly liquid, short-term debt instruments. Its primary goal is to maintain a stable net asset value (NAV) while paying out monthly interest based on prevailing central bank rates.</p>
    <p>In Canada, there has been a massive surge in "High-Interest Savings Account (HISA) ETFs" like <strong>CASH.TO</strong> (Horizons) or <strong>PSA</strong> (Purpose). Rather than buying government bonds, these ETFs literally just deposit the pooled investor money into wholesale banking accounts that pay a higher institutional interest rate than a retail consumer could ever get.</p>

    <h2>Money Market Funds vs. HYSA</h2>
    <p>If both a <a href="/best-hysa-canada-2026">High-Yield Savings Account (HYSA)</a> and a Money Market ETF pay roughly the same interest rate, why choose one over the other?</p>

    <h3>The Case for Money Market ETFs</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Brokerage Convenience:</strong> If you sell a stock and don't want to reinvest immediately, you can buy a money market ETF right there in the same account to instantly start earning interest.</li>
      <li><strong>Registered Account Access:</strong> It is difficult to get high HYSA rates inside a TFSA or RRSP at traditional banks. You can hold a cash ETF inside your registered brokerage account easily.</li>
      <li><strong>Institutional Rates:</strong> HISA ETFs often track the Bank of Canada overnight rate very closely, reacting faster than retail banks.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>The Case for an HYSA</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>CDIC / FDIC Insurance:</strong> Money in a bank account is legally insured against bank failure up to a certain limit. Money market ETFs do not have this legal guarantee (though the underlying banks they deposit into do, but the structure is different).</li>
      <li><strong>Immediate Liquidity:</strong> You can pay a bill directly from an HYSA via e-Transfer or debit. Selling an ETF takes a couple of days to settle before you can withdraw the cash to your checking account.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Tax Treatment of Money Market Funds</h2>
    <p>Don't let the term "ETF" fool you. In Canada, the monthly distributions from HISA ETFs like CASH.TO are classified as <strong>Interest Income</strong>, not capital gains or eligible dividends.</p>
    <p>This means if you hold these funds in a non-registered (taxable) account, the income is fully taxed at your highest marginal tax rate. For high-income earners on the path to FIRE, this can severely diminish the after-tax return.</p>
    <p>Because of this tax treatment, money market funds are best held inside tax-advantaged accounts like a TFSA or RRSP, or compared closely against the after-tax returns of <a href="/treasury-bills-guide">Treasury Bills</a> or corporate bonds.</p>

    <h2>Where do they fit in a FIRE Strategy?</h2>
    <p>Money market funds are perfect for holding your "dry powder"—cash you intend to invest but are holding back for tactical reasons, or cash generated from dividends inside your brokerage.</p>
    <p>However, for your core emergency fund, a traditional HYSA or a <a href="/best-gic-rates-2026">GIC ladder</a> often provides slightly better legal protections and easier, immediate access.</p>
    <p>Read our overarching guide to see how these funds stack up against all the other options in our <a href="/cash-savings-compared">Cash Savings Compared</a> overview.</p>
  </div>

